            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Aarav Sharma\u2019s world is contained within the concrete walls and expansive glass of his SOMA live/work loft, a universe of his own design. The 0.0-mile commute is a luxury he earned. Born in Fremont to Indian immigrants who saw Silicon Valley as the promised land, Aarav\u2019s path was meant to be paved with code. His parents, an engineer and a pharmacist, celebrated his acceptance into UC Davis for Computer Science, viewing it as the final step toward a stable, lucrative career.\n\nBut while Aarav excelled in programming, his electives in art history and architecture were his true passion. He spent weekends wandering through SFMOMA, captivated not by the paintings, but by the way the space itself told a story. After graduating, he dutifully took a software engineering job, but the sterile conformity of his cubicle felt like a cage. The turning point came during a volunteer stint at the Exploratorium, where he helped fabricate a small interactive display. The fusion of logic, technology, and tangible art was a revelation.\n\nAt 28, he made a terrifying leap. He quit his six-figure tech job, enrolled in design courses, and took on freelance gigs building digital models for small galleries. His parents were dismayed, seeing it as a foolish regression. For years, family gatherings were tense, his career a topic of gentle but persistent concern.\n\nNow, at 41, Aarav is a sought-after exhibit designer. His loft is a testament to his journey, with one side dedicated to high-powered computers for 3D modeling and the other to a workshop filled with sketches, miniature models, and material samples. His days are a quiet rhythm of coffee from the cafe downstairs, intense digital work, and hands-on creation. His social life revolves around a tight-knit circle of curators, artists, and fabricators\u2014his chosen family. He has a cordial, if still slightly distant, relationship with his parents, who now boast of his work in museums, even if they don\u2019t fully understand it.\n\nAarav\u2019s dream is to design a permanent wing for a major institution, a space that will outlive him. More deeply, he hopes to create an exhibit that truly honors his heritage, bridging the ancient stories of India with the interactive technology of his adopted home, finally making his two worlds one."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers standing on the oculus bridge at SFMOMA, age 20. He wasn\u2019t looking at the Calder mobile, but at the light flooding the atrium. It was the first time he understood space as a language\u2014the curve of the wall, the flow of the staircase telling a story more profound than any painting. The realization was a quiet, internal tremor. It was then he knew the architecture of his life, not just the code within it, was what truly mattered. That day marked the beginning of his secret rebellion.\n\n2.\nAt 27, volunteering at the Exploratorium, he was soldering a tiny circuit board. When he connected the last wire, the display hummed to life, light pulsing in response to sound. In that flash, his two selves\u2014the engineer and the artist\u2014collided and fused. The sterile logic of code became a tool for tangible wonder. It wasn't just a fun project; it was a complete, electrifying vision of a possible future. He knew then that he couldn't stay in his cubicle. The cage now had a key.\n\n3.\nThe weight of the silence in his parents\u2019 Fremont kitchen, age 28, was heavier than any shouting match. He\u2019d just told them he\u2019d quit his job. His mother stirred her dal, refusing to meet his eyes, while his father\u2019s face was a mask of profound disappointment. It wasn't anger; it was fear for his future. The moment was terrifying but clarifying. In their silence, he found his own voice, learning that forging his own path meant accepting he might have to, for a time, walk it alone.\n\n4.\nHe was 31, broke, and full of doubt. He stood anonymously in a tiny Tenderloin gallery, watching a child mesmerized by his first paid commission\u2014a simple kinetic sculpture. The girl reached out a tentative finger, making the wooden gears turn and light patterns shift. Aarav felt a wave of relief so powerful it almost buckled his knees. This was it. Not money or prestige, but this quiet, shared moment of wonder. It was the fuel he needed to keep going, the first real proof he was right.\n\n5.\nTwo years ago, during a visit home, he overheard his father on the phone. \"Yes, the new exhibit at the city museum\u2026 my son Aarav designed it.\" The words were spoken with a stilted, unfamiliar pride. Aarav stood unseen in the hallway, his breath caught in his throat. It wasn't an apology, but it was a bridge. He finally understood that their approval wasn't the goal, but receiving it, however obliquely, allowed a decade of quiet heartache to finally dissolve. It felt like coming home."
        },
